\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The purpose of presuppositional apologetics is to defeat the requirement of providing empirical evidence for god.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In the secular view, belief in any given claim is a justified belief only if the claim meets some evidentiary burden. Consider, for example, the claim that there is a teapot orbiting Jupiter. One is justified in believing this claim if there exists evidence to support it. If we point a satellite at Jupiter and receive data which suggests there is a teapot orbiting Jupiter, we would be justified in holding the belief. If we are not able to gather any evidence to support the claim, we would not be justified in holding to the belief.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Many people believe in a deity. Some of these people want to claim that their belief in a deity is justified. But if a justified belief is an empirically evidenced belief, then the deity claim is not justified, as it has not been empirically evidenced.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Some might claim that there is empirical evidence for some given deity. Perhaps they have personally witnessed a ghost, heard a foreign voice in their head, had a revelatory near-death experience, or otherwise witnessed a miracle. Regardless of the veracity of these claims, the interpretation that these experiences are divinely inspired does not necessarily follow from the raw facts. It is known that such experiences can have as their cause illness, such as parkinsons, or perhaps it was some drug-induced state, or an allergic reaction, migraine hallucinations, or simply a magician\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s trick, as James Randi can attest.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Nestled inside that set of theists who want their theistic beliefs to be justified is a subset who also believe that theistic claims have not provided sufficient emperical proof of the claims. So what then? Enter presuppositional apologetics. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The purpose of persuppositional apologetics is to refocus the entire concept of justified belief, and lead it away from any empirical commitments.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The tactic is as follows.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 PA = presupp apologist}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 SR = Standard response}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 PA: You say you will only believe something if you have empirical proof. But why do you believe empirical proof necessarily leads to truth?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 SR: Because empirical proof is the most reliable way of investigating reality.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 PA: But how do you know that there such a thing as reality that empircal proof corresponds to?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 SR: I don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t. It\u8217\'92s impossible to say that. That is the hard problem of solipsism - that we can\u8217\'92t actually prove that an external world exists. To do anything we must simply assume that it does exist. But I\u8217\'92m comfortable making that assumption.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 PA: So you have a belief that external reality exists, but you have no actual empirical evidence that it does. Therefore, there are some beliefs that are justifiable that do not require empirical evidence.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 SR: Sure. But God is not one of those beliefs. Assuming the external world exists is a requirement to learn anything. I am not required to believe that God exists to do that. So the God claim belongs to a different category of claims than the claim of external reality.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 PA: Au contraire. If you pressuppose that an external reality exists and that you can learn about, aren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t you also presupposing the claim that logic and reason are reliable? After all, how can you learn about something if logic and reason aren\u8217\'92t reliable?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 SR: I don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t think it\u8217\'92s necessary to presuppose that logic and reason are reliable. It think that becomes self-evident through induction. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 PA: Then you have no ultimate grounding for anything that you know about external reality.  If your trust in the reliability of logic only comes through induction, then you *could* be wrong about it. This is the standard problem of induction, no?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 SR: Sure.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 PA: Then you must see how all of your knowledge is hollow, how you can\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t be certain of anything. }
