\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Presuppositionalists contrast their approach with the other schools of Christian apologetics by describing the others as assuming that the world is intelligible apart from belief in the existence of God and then arguing on purportedly neutral grounds to support trusting the Christian\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scripture"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Scriptures}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~and the existence of God. Specifically, presuppositionalists describe\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Aquinas"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Thomistic}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~(also "Traditional" or "Classical") apologetics as concentrating on the first aspect of apologetics with its\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_argument"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 logical proofs}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~for the existence of God, simply assuming common ground with the non-Christian and using a piece-by-piece methodology. In this scheme, the common foundation of neutral\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brute_fact"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 brute facts}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~leads to a generic concept of deity, then to the various characteristics of the Christian God as revealed in Scripture, and so forth. Piece-by-piece, Christian theology is built up from a neutral common ground.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Presuppositionalists assert that many of the classical arguments are logically fallacious, or do not prove enough, when used as arguments to prove the existence or character of God.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presuppositional_apologetics#cite_note-5"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 a]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~They criticize both the assumption of neutrality and the "block house" or "piecemeal" method for failing to start at the level of the controlling beliefs of worldviews and implicitly allowing non-Christian assumptions from the start, thereby trying to build a Christian "house" on a non-Christian "foundation".}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presuppositional_apologetics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEvan_Til1967122%E2%80%9323,_126%E2%80%9329,_131%E2%80%9332-6"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 5]}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presuppositional_apologetics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBahnsen1998266%E2%80%9368-7"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 6]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Evidentialists demur from this assessment, claiming that presuppositionalism amounts to\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fideism"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 fideism}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~because it rejects the idea of shared points of reference between the Christian and non-Christian from which they may reason in common.}{ }
