\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Apologists who follow Van Til earned the label "presuppositional" because of their central tenet that the Christian must at all times presuppose the supernatural revelation of the Bible as the ultimate arbiter of truth and error in order to know anything. Christians, they say, can assume nothing less because all human thought presupposes the existence of the God of the Bible.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 They claim that by accepting the assumptions of non-Christians, which fundamentally deny the\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trinity"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Trinitarian}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~God of the Bible, one could not even formulate an intelligible argument.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 According to Frame, "[Van Til's] major complaints against competing apologetic methods are theological complaints, that is, that they compromise the incomprehensibility of God,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_depravity"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 total depravity}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , the clarity of natural revelation, God's comprehensive control over\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creation_myth"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 creation}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , and so on."}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Within their presuppositionalist framework, Van Tillians do often use foundational concepts for Thomistic and Evidentialist arguments (belief in the uniformity of natural causes, for example), but they are unwilling to grant that such beliefs are justifiable on "natural" (neutral) grounds. Rather, Van Tillians employ these beliefs, which they justify on Biblical grounds, in the service of\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendental_arguments"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i1 transcendental arguments}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , which are a sort of meta-argument about foundational principles, necessary preconditions, in which the non-Christian's worldview is shown to be incoherent in and of itself and intelligible only because it borrows capital from the Christian worldview.\~}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Van Til summarized the main drive of his apologetic by saying: "the only proof for the existence of God is that without God you couldn't prove anything."}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 he primary job of the apologist is, therefore, simply to confront the unbeliever with the fact that, while he is verbally denying the truth, he is nonetheless practically behaving in accord with it. Van Til illustrated this alleged inconsistency as a child, elevated on the father's knee, reaching up to slap his face, and Bahnsen used the analogy of a man breathing out air to make the argument that air doesn't exist.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Another important aspect of the Van Tillian apologetical program is the distinction between\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 proof}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~and\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 persuasion}{\f0\fs24\b0 . According to the first chapter of the\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epistle_to_the_Romans"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Epistle to the Romans}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , man has ample proof in all of creation of God's existence and attributes but chooses to suppress it.}{ }
