\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Testing for internal contradiction exemplifies Clark's strict reliance on the\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_logic"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 laws of logic}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~(he famously translates the first verse of the Gospel of John as "In the beginning was the Logic, and the Logic was with God, and the Logic was God.")}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presuppositional_apologetics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEClark1998115%E2%80%9322-31"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 29]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Thus, in order to invalidate non-Christian worldviews, one must simply show how a different presupposition results in necessary logical contradictions, while showing that presupposing the Bible leads to no logical contradiction. By contrast, some Van Tillians have suggested that God as He has revealed Himself in Scripture reveals apparent paradoxes.}{ }
\par\plain 
